  <li id="comment-72351" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Sarah J</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2018/11/november-28/#comment-72351"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2019-04-21T12:47:07-04:00">Sunday, April 21, 2019 at 12:47 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I love coming back to your blog now and then. I&#8217;m never sure what brings me back, but that each time there is something I haven&#8217;t seen before, and a connection to myself way back when I first discovered your work. Many will be awaiting your book, and you just keep being you.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-73734" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://thebackcountrykitchen.com/" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">The Backcountry Kitchen</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2018/11/november-28/#comment-73734"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2019-06-20T22:03:05-04:00">Thursday, June 20, 2019 at 10:03 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi Molly! I miss this. Your voice is incredible and such an inspiration for other bloggers. I keep coming back to your blog for inspiration and never stop admiring your writing style. You should always write what you feel called to!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-74521" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Caren</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2018/11/november-28/#comment-74521"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2019-08-25T06:04:07-04:00">Sunday, August 25, 2019 at 6:04 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>‚Äú always said that I‚Äôd be clear about the end of this blog when the time came, but then the end came and went and I hardly noticed.‚Äù</p>
<p>When I read that, I was reminded of  a friend who said, ‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt know when it might be the last time you do something with your kids. The other day, I realized Cory [her oldest] hadn‚Äôt asked to be carried in some time. When was the last time I carried him? I have no idea. There was no way for me to know, nothing telling me to notice, ‚ÄòThis is the very last time.‚Äô‚Äù</p>
<p>It‚Äôs because kids grow and life most often changes in increments. Things shift and change all along until one day, you become aware you‚Äôre not where you used to be. It can seem all-of-a-sudden &#8211; ‚ÄúWhen did you grow out of these pants? Didn‚Äôt you wear them just last week?‚Äù; ‚ÄúWell. OK. I‚Äôll get your things together, and leave them by the front doorstep.‚Äù &#8211;  when really, things were evolving, at an unnoticeable and maybe only minimally felt pace, the whole time.</p>
<p>We mark and note the firsts, but lasts are often seen only with time. Sudden changes, like unexpected death, calamities, accidents &#8230; can make them stand out in relief for a time, but normally, they slip by.</p>
<p>I‚Äôm so glad you‚Äôre still writing!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
